# Environment Variables

Copy `.env.example` to `.env` and fill in your Jira credentials:

```bash
cp .env.example .env
```

## Required Variables

```
JIRA_BASE_URL=https://your-jira-instance.com
JIRA_USERNAME=your-username
JIRA_PASSWORD=your-password
```

## Optional Variables - HTTP Server Configuration

```
# MCP HTTP Server Configuration
MCP_HOST=127.0.0.1  # HTTP server host (default: 127.0.0.1)
MCP_PORT=3000       # HTTP server port (default: 3000)

# Jira API Configuration
JIRA_API_VERSION=2  # API version (default: 2)

# Jira Credentials (Optional)
# If not set here, credentials must be provided by MCP clients during initialization
# JIRA_USERNAME=your-username
# JIRA_PASSWORD=your-password
```

## MCP Endpoint

The server exposes a single MCP endpoint at:
`http://<MCP_HOST>:<MCP_PORT>/mcp`

This endpoint supports:
- POST requests for tool calls and other MCP operations
- GET requests for SSE streaming (when enabled)

## Client-Side Credentials Configuration

Jira credentials can be provided by MCP clients during the initialize request.
The client should include credentials in the `_meta` field:

```json
{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 1,
  "method": "initialize",
  "params": {
    "protocolVersion": "2025-11-25",
    "capabilities": {},
    "clientInfo": {
      "name": "your-client",
      "version": "1.0.0"
    },
    "_meta": {
      "credentials": {
        "username": "jira-user",
        "password": "jira-password"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This allows each MCP client to use its own credentials, making the server suitable for shared deployment.
